The patient's concurrent conditions included progressive multiple sclerosis, swelling of the left leg and foot, and non smoker, and other pre-existing medical conditions included the patient had no known drug allergies. the patient was not a pregnant at the time of reporting. The patient had no family history of thrombosis, no prior deep vein thrombosis (DVT). The patient received covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s (suspension for injection, route of admin not reported, batch number: 1808609, expiry: UNKNOWN) dose was not reported, 1 total, administered on 22-MAR-2021 for prophylactic vaccination. Concomitant medications included baclofen, escitalopram oxalate, and risedronate sodium (received 2 doses and stopped after the event).  The patient's husband reported that in MAR-2021, the patient had symptoms of fatigue.  On 23-MAR-2021, the patient had swelling and fatigue.  Her fatigue was resolved on 24-MAR-2021 and swelling was resolving.  On 05-APR-2021, the patient developed left thigh swelling. On 06-APR-2021, the patient's swelling was not going down and she visited her primary care physician. The physician could not determine the cause of swelling (left thigh very noticeable clot swollen around where clot was located) and the physician suspected clot and performed an AD dimer (fibrin degradation) test to look for potential blood clotting. The patient also had a venous duplex ultrasound that showed left leg clot.  At 19:00 on the same day, the patient's physician advised to visit emergency room and determined there was a clot on left thigh and she was prescribed Eliquis Starter Pack (apixaban) for 3 months treatment and recommended another scan in several months. On 06-APR-2021, the patient's vitals were reported as blood pressure 124/70 mmHg, heart rate 88 bpm and oxygen saturation of 99%. Laboratory data included prothrombin time (PT) 13.4 sec , International normalized ratio (INR) 1.2 and  activated partial thromboplastin time  (APTT) 34.8 sec. (Normal range not reported for all) d-dimer and platelet count results were not available and Covid-19 test was not performed. Body max index was 19.5 kg/m2. On an unspecified date the patient was feeling better but had not recovered from the event. The action taken with covid-19 vaccine ad26.cov2.s was not applicable. The patient recovered from fatigue on 24-MAR-2021, had not recovered from blood clot in left thigh, and recovering from swelling. This report was serious (Other Medically Important Condition).; Sender's Comments: V0: This case concerns a 55-year- old female subject, immobile due to progressive multiple sclerosis who developed a left thigh swelling 12 days after Janssen COVID-19 vaccine was administered intramuscularly for the prevention of symptomatic SARS-CoV-2 virus infection.  The patient's concurrent conditions included body max index of 19.5 kg/m2, progressive multiple sclerosis and swelling of the left leg and foot. She is a non-smoker, no known drug allergies, no family history of thrombosis, or prior deep vein thrombosis (DVT). Symptoms started with swelling of the left thigh and fatigue. The fatigue resolved the next day. The patient's swelling in the left thigh was not going down and she visited her primary care physician who checked her D-dimer dimer (level not known to patient) and scheduled a venous duplex ultrasound that showed a clot in the left thigh.  Her vital signs were blood pressure of  124/70 mmHg, heart rate 88 bpm and oxygen saturation of 99%. and she was prescribed Eliquis Starter Pack (apixaban) for 3 months treatment and recommended another scan in several months. Laboratory data included PT 13.4 sec, INR 1.2 and APTT 34.8 sec. D-dimer and platelet count results were not available and Covid-19 test was not performed. The patient is feeling better but had not recovered from blood clot in the left thigh, and is recovering from the swelling. Given underlying progressive multiple sclerosis with immobility and preexisting swelling of the left leg and foot on the same lower extremity, the clotting of the left thigh is considered not related to Janssen COVID-19 vaccine. Additional information has been requested.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I could not open my eyes; associated with Mild flushed; EPISODIC Parosymal Hypertension/hypertensive episode lasted for 5 hours to 7hours per day/ highest BP at home was 216/95 mmhg/ episode of Paroxysmal hypertensive episode associated with tachycardia.; I developed a continuous tearing & watery nasal dripping that lasted for 7 hours; episode associated with tachycardia; I developed a continuous tearing & watery nasal dripping that lasted for 7 hours; I was not feeling well; This is a spontaneous report from a contactable physician (patient). A 71-year-old patient of an unspecified gender received first dose of BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE) via an unspecified route of administration administered in left arm on 25Feb2021 10:00 (Lot Number: EN6200) as single dose for COVID-19 immunisation. Medical history included thyroid cancer, hypertension, Sjogren's syndrome, hyperlipidaemia. Concomitant medication included amlodipine, aspirin, atorvastatin calcium (ATORVAS). No other vaccine was received in four weeks. No covid prior vaccination. The patient previously took lisinopril and experienced allergy (caused cough). The patient underwent COVID test  via nasal swab post vaccination on 08Mar2021 and result was negative. 2 days after receiving vaccine on 27Feb2021, the patient developed a continuous tearing and watery nasal dripping that lasted for 7 hours. At that time, the patient could not open eyes and the patient was not feeling well. and then one and off episode of paroxysmal hypertensive episode associated with tachycardia. Highest BP at home was 216/95 mmHg and worsening PR was 126/4min. Associated with mild flushed but not associated with clammy, no dyspnea, no nausea or vomiting, no diarrhea, no right side abdominal pain. This hypertensive episode lasted for 5 hours to 7 hours per day. The patient contacted to primary care doctor twice in different days. The patient was brought to ER where the patient got first Pfizer shot. Stayed one night 5 as observation patient on 08Mar2021 and next day 09Mar2021, the patient was admitted to Medicine floor. During hopitalization, this episodic parosymal hypertension was continued SBP was up to 211 and finally discharged from hospital on 21Mar2021. The events resulted in emergency room/department or urgent care, hospitalization, life threatening illness (immediate risk of death from the event. Extensive work up was done. No treatment was received for events. The outcome of events was recovering.; Sender's Comments: Based on vaccine-event chronological association, a causal relationship between reported events and BNT162B2 (PFIZER-BIONTECH COVID-19 VACCINE) cannot be completely excluded. The case will be reevaluated should additional information become available.

respiratory and cardiac arrest Narrative:  Patient with PMH of esophageal cancer, larynx cancer, liver cancer, PTSD, A. fib, and alcohol abuse. He received his COVID-19 vaccines on 2/14/21 and 3/14/21. Both vaccines were administered without complications and patient was observed for 15 minutes post-vaccination without adverse effects. No other adverse events noted between time of last COVID-19 vaccinations and death. On 4/11/21, patient's wife called 911 in which EMS found patient unresponsive with abnormal breathing. Wife reported that patient was breathing up until 5 minutes prior to EMA arrival, but had been unresponsive. Wife reports that patient suffered from multiple forms of cancer, PTSD, and alcohol abuse. Wife believed that patient quit smoking and drinking but the morning of death found vodka and cigarettes in his coat. Wife reports that patient asked for help getting up from the stairs and then laid down in the bed, and went unresponsive afterwards. EMS attempted to revive the patient with CPR but were unsuccessful. Per EMS note patient suffered from respiratory arrest, cardiac arrest, then cardiac death. Patient was not brought to the hospital prior to death. It is very unlikely that the COVID-19 vaccinations contributed to this patient's death due to his extensive PMH with substance use disorder and cancer.

Chest pain; Shortness of breath; Fever; Chills; Dizziness; Diaphoresis; This case was obtained on 04APR2021 in the review of scientific publications.  This is case 5 of 5 (cross reference: 18000140LT, 18000141LT, 18000142LT, and 18000143LT).   A 23 year old healthy female experienced suspected myopericarditis following vaccination with ACAM2000.  In April 2018, the patient received a first dose of ACAM2000 (Lot Unknown). Approximately 8-11 days after vaccination, she presented to the Emergency department with an acute onset of chest pain but without complaints of recent body aches, fever, or respiratory symptoms that may be suggestive of influenza-type illness. Other clinical signs at presentation included shortness of breath, diaphoresis, dizziness, chills and fever. Her troponin was negative. She received follow up care with a cardiologist for 6 months and underwent serial cardiac imaging. Additionally she was placed on limited duty with no exercise for six weeks with non-deployable status for at least six months.  She was followed by a Cardiologist until complete recovery at between three and nine months.  Laboratory Data included:  Flu A/B (rapid Ag) - Negative Coxsackie A7, A9, A16, A24, (IgG/IgM) - A-9/A-24 IgG*/IgM- Parvo B19 (IgG/IgM) - IgG+/IgM- Epstein Interpretation - Past Infection Epstein Barr Virus Capsid Ab IgG - Positive Epstein Barr Virus Ab - Negative Epstein-Barr Virus Capsid Ab IgM - Negative  Epstein Barr Virus Early Ab IgG - Negative Epstein Barr Virus Nuclear Ab IgG - Positive Adenovirus Ab - Negative Cytomegalovirus DNA PCR - Negative Viral Culture - Negative Enterovirus - Negative Parechovirus - Negative  The authors concluded that there was no significant difference observed between the rate seen and the published rates that occurred during the clinical trials. The available evidence suggested that the 5 cases were not an unexpected elevation in the rate of the disease or condition, but rather a predictable number of myopericarditis cases proportional to the increased number of vaccinations performed during a short period of time.  Company comments: This article was a retrospective analysis and detail of the cases were not specific. This case was associated with a suspected  myocarditis. In the manuscript categorized myocarditis or pericarditis as "data insufficient to adjudicate" in cases of subclinical myopericarditis. The same case applies in this case. The patient had chest pain but troponin was normal, no indication that an ECG was done, she was treated as an outpatient and the follow up with cardiologists did not make the diagnosis. For this reason, myocarditis was not recorded as an adverse event but the symptoms. The company considers that the chest pain, dyspnea, fever and chills are possible related but dizziness and hyperhidrosis as not assessable. More information will be requested.; Sender's Comments: Company comments: This article was a retrospective analysis and detail of the cases were not specific. This case was associated with a suspected  myocarditis. In the manuscript categorized myocarditis or pericarditis as "data insufficient to adjudicate" in cases of subclinical myopericarditis. The same case applies in this case. The patient had chest pain but troponin was normal, no indication that an ECG was done, she was treated as an outpatient and the follow up with cardiologists did not make the diagnosis. For this reason, myocarditis was not recorded as an adverse event but the symptoms. The company considers that the chest pain, dyspnea, fever and chills are possible related but dizziness and hyperhidrosis as not assessable. More information will be requested. SYMPTOM_TEXT: 86-year-old spanish speaking female brought into the ED with concerns of slurred speech and confusion that was noted at 3 PM on 4/8.  Patient's last known well was at 10 AM on 4/8.  GCS on arrival 15.  NIH SS 2 recorded at 18: 12 (for mild right-sided facial droop and mild dysarthria).   In the EMS blood glucose was 122, no meds were given.  Patient is not on any anticoagulation.  Patient's blood pressure was elevated at 233/78.  Patient denying any headaches, nausea, vomiting.  Per the family no focal neurologic deficits noted except for dysarthria which was improved during the ED visit.   Neurology contacted in the ED for stroke code.  Patient outside of TPA window.  CT head was negative.  CT head negative for acute intracranial infarction.  Chest x-ray negative for any acute cardiopulmonary findings.  Patient was started on nicardipine drip in the ED with the blood pressure reduced to 145/70, then turned off.  CBC showed mild leukocytosis (14.8) likely reactive.  CMP unremarkable.  PT/INR was also obtained.   After discussion with neurology given the CT head and CTA head and neck, CTP negative are reassuring for low concern of stroke. ASA 325 once was given. However neurology does recommend an admission for further evaluation with an MRI for notably rule out stroke.  After discussion with family and the physicians the patient refused admission.   Upon reexamination no further worsening of her initial symptoms, blood pressure controlled.  Patient was discharged in a stable condition.  She was discharged AMA.  Patient was thoroughly explained the risks and benefits of leaving AMA.  Patient said she understood and was advised to come back if the symptoms worsen.  Patient was discharged with aspirin, Plavix and atorvastatin.  Recommended to follow-up with the PCP tomorrow soon as possible.  Also advised to return to the ED if any of the symptoms return.

At day 13 after the shot, I noticed that my left breast was swollen, had pitted skin like an orange, was red, and had a large ridge through it. I am nursing and though possibly I had an infection, but never developed severe pain or fever as with mastitis. On  able to consult with a doctor on 5 March. He ordered an ultrasound of the breast to rule out any malignancies. The ultrasound found a superficial thrombophlebitis in the breast under the exact area of swelling, discoloration, and skin puckering.  After 3 weeks, the swelling has disappeared and the breast only remains slightly discolored the chorded vein is no longer able the be felt as it was previously.
LAB_DATA: The  ultrasound found the following:  FINDINGS: Immediately subcutaneous noncompressible hypoechoic tubular structure at the 10:00 to 12:00 position 2 cm from the nipple without discernible internal flow corresponds to the palpable abnormality in the location of previous skin abnormality.   IMPRESSION:   Resolving superficial thrombophlebitis of a small superficial vein within the medial upper left breast. No evidence of malignancy.   Discussion: Findings may have been attributable to transient lymphatic congestion from recent vaccine injection. Symptoms appear to be improving. Patient instructed to seek medical treatment if recurrent symptoms of infection

Got the vaccine and waited the 15 minutes per their recommendations, and while driving her car home within 10 minutes felt that her face, bridge of her nose and spreading into her cheeks became numb and tingling.  Then the lower part of her face, spreading down into her windpipe and clavicle area, then her  (outer 2 toes on each foot, pinky and next finger) started to get numb and tingly, as well as the upper lip.  As the day wore on that evening the feeling went to the either side of her spine, the numbness and tingling.  She waited to see if it dissipated, and called her doctor on Monday 3/15/21 and saw a PA who felt that she may have upset her whole nerve system and told her that it was going to take a while for it to straighten out.  She consulted with her PCP and gave her some samples of Horizant, but she did not try it as she has multiple allergies to medications.   She also from the time of her vaccine that she started to get horrible burning and tingling throughout her body everywhere, (arms, stomach) woke her up from sleep.   The other symptoms previously mentioned continued as well.  On Wednesday 3/17/21, called her cardiologist who told her to call the hospital and perhaps go to the hospital and they told her to call her doctor.  The cardiologist told her she needed to see a neurologist who she saw on 3/31/21.  The patient was afraid she had Guillain Barre syndrome, and the neurologist felt that if that was the case and that she would not have been able to walk at this point.  She did the neurologic testing, and she was going to give her Gabapentin (which she had already been given samples of and did not want to take).  The burning and tightness of her face down to her throat/clavicle area was concerning to her and still continues.  Her conclusion was that if she got worse to go to the hospital, and the basically do not know what to do.  She herself is wanting to know if this is going to disappear, and what are the long-term affects.  She is now hesitant to have her eyes dilated, is scheduled for some procedures and afraid to have them done as it has been 5 weeks since the vaccine and still having the same reactions, and does not know what she should do.    Since the vaccine the worst is in the morning, and residual in the face/burning of her face to throat/clavicle, and also continues with the burning in her spine as well.  The burning is not as bad as it was, but the face, throat/clavicle area is the worst.

Pt was found in severe distress in the bathroom by his wife.  He couldn't walk or stand, complained of being dizzy with slurred speech and was throwing up a lot. 911 was immediately called. The EMTs during their assessment said his BP was normal but when he was asked his name, he started saying the alphabet"ABC... XYZ".  He was transported by ambulance to ER. Cat scan showed he had a bleed on the brain.  The doctors told us it was because he had very high blood pressure, however where the bleed was, they said he wouldn't need surgery and that the body would reabsorb it over time.  He was admitted to the ICU and has been there ever since.  Several days later, he started having difficulty breathing and they discovered several blood clots in his right leg that had broken off into his heart and lungs.  He had emergency surgery to remove the clots in his heart (approximately 10) and was given heparin in small doses over an 8 hour period so that it wouldn't cause the bleed in his brain to increase.  The doctor should fill in the rest.

I developed numbness that started in my toes which gradually progressed up my legs and then into my hands. This course progressed over a period of 5-6 days. I was initially seen at the Medical Center on 2/8/21 in the ER. Neurology was consulted for my symptoms, suspecting sensory/small fiber acute inflammatory demyelination process such as Gillian Barre Syndrome. At that time, other than the sensory changes, I did not have weakness or ataxia/gait instability, so I was sent home from the ER.   The following day, while I was at work, I had some difficulty with my balance. I had spoken to my Neurologist, and decision was made for a direct admission for IVIG treatment. I was admitted to the Medical Center on 2/9/2021 for a 2 day course of IVIG (receiving a total of 2g/kg dose over the two days). I was d/c from the hospital on 2/11/2021. I did not require any rehabilitation and was discharged home.   Following discharge, I developed painful neuropathy in my feet, and was started on Pamelor for treatment. Due to side effects of the medication, I was switched to Cymbalta which is what I am on now for neuropathic pain. I continue to have numbness in my hands and feet, but it has not continue to progress at this time.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: A week following my mothers vaccination, she became increasing fatigued. On day 10 following her vaccination she went to bed and had to be helped to her room, this was unusual. She remained in bed for 19-20 hours a day for three days. I called all of her doctors, all of whom she had just been seen by, routine CT scans performed, blood work done, and visit with her neurologist. Her oncologist suggested we seek a hospice evaluation, even though her CT scans showed that her cancer had only slight growth, nothing to be concerned about. Her primary care office ordered the hospice evaluation and it was performed on Thursday, 3/18. They said ?she may just be having a bad week following her vaccination? and ?lets revisit this the following week?. her condition continued to deteriorate significantly over the next few days, so much that she began sleeping 21?23 hours a day. On the following Tuesday, 3/23, she was admitted into the hospice system. Now, four weeks later, we are in the final weeks of her life. She refuses food and water now, and her nurse says that it won?t be much longer. She went from a relatively healthily, senior woman, with underlying health issues, none of which presented her imminent demise, to dying at home within weeks of receiving her J&J vaccine. I have no idea if he demise is in anyway related to her vaccine, but thought it was important to report her symptoms.

I cannot confidently rule out the Vaccine as the cause, and what I know of my body suggests in fact some "overdrive" function in my system was triggered and then caused the crash that resulted in infection and that continues to interfere with my walking, eating, moving, breathing, and even drinking a small glass of water today. Her shortness of breath progressively worsened, and she was seen by another provider as a walk-in at the office of her PCP on 03/13/2021.  At that time, she was prescribed prednisone for 5 days, noting some improvement after a few days.  She received her 2nd Pfizer COVID vaccine on 03/19/2021.  The patient woke up on the morning of 03/20/21 with a swollen and painful leg and by 03/22/21 called PCP and was seen in the office.  PCP ordered D-Dimer and LE ultrasound. SYMPTOM_TEXT: April 5th, one week after receiving the vaccine, I began to experience chills, extreme skin sensitivity, and ran a low-grade fever. This continued, with the skin pain worsening on the right side of my torso, until Thursday, April 8th, when a rash appeared on the right side of my stomach. By that night, I also had rash spots on my back (also the right side) and other small spots on my torso, with blisters starting to form on the patch on my stomach. The pain and rash were entirely on the right side of my torso. Friday morning (April 9th), I did a Telehealth visit and was diagnosed with shingles. I was prescribed an anti-viral which I began taking Friday evening. The symptoms began going away by Saturday afternoon and continue to heal. I finished the anti-virals course on Friday, April 16th, and as of today, April 19th, the rashes are almost all completely gone, I have no fever, and only a few small pain spots.
OTHER_MEDS: Amitriptyline 100mg the night before; atorvastatin calcium 20 mg the night before; iron supplement; multivitamin; flaxseed
HISTORY: Fibromyalgia, eczema, psoriasis, high cholesterol, chronic bronchitis

I received the J&J vaccine at 10:00am on March 18, 2021 at the Community Center. By about 5:00pm, I started to feel minor flu-like symptoms, but as the night progressed it got significantly worse. Around 8-9pm, I was bedridden with the worst chills/shaking I've ever experienced in my life. Around 9:30-10:00pm, I was filling water at my sink and projectile vomitted multiple times into the sink and could not make it to the bathroom. Subsequently, I ate a bagel and drank lots of water, knowing my vomitting could make me dehydrated. Throughout the night, I was awake and shaking, and drank and filled my water bottle repeatedly. At 8:00am, I was filling my water, and without my knowledge of awareness, fainted on my kitchen floor, dropping the Brita filter and likely hitting my head. My roommate heard the commotion and saw me passed out in our kitchen. He tried to wake me up and I phased in, but then subsequently phased out again 20-30 seconds later as I was trying to stand and likely hit my head again. My roommate eventually got me over to our couch and called EMTs. Upon their arrival, EMTs checked my pulse, which was fine, and saw an open laceration on the back of my head, so they took me to Hospital to access the Trauma Center. On the way, I threw up repeatedly and was very lightheaded. Upon my arrival at Hospital, I was checked for any neck bone breaks, given an IV, a CT  scan, an EKG, and staples were placed in the back of my head to heal the laceration. After my release, I was bedridden for 2-3 days and required a daily nap during work (1-2) hours for the next 1 1/2 to 2 weeks. For a while, everything was fine, but recently during the first two weeks of April, it has become apparent that my head is foggy and reacts to changes in the weather, which leads me to believe that I likely banged my head pretty good when I fainted those two times.
LAB_DATA: My EKG, cat scan, blood pressure, heart rate, and pulse were all normal and consistent with my prior EKGs and naturally low blood sugar and pulse.
OTHER_MEDS: No prescriptions. No dietary supplements. No herbal remedies.
ALLERGIES: Allergic to certain nuts, including macadamia, pistachio, and cashews.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient was vaccinated at 04:25 PM and at 04:35 PM began to feel dizzy. She reported feeling warm, flushed, heart palpitations,  dizzy, itchy, and felt as if her legs were heavy. She reported symptoms to nursing staff at 05:00 PM. She stated she did not feel she could stand but was able to pivot herself to a wheel chair. She was taken to the triage area and was also able to stand and move herself to the cot to lay down. She did report dizziness increased with movement. Vitals at 5 PM were BP 140/72, HR 125, O2 96% on room air. She denied any breathing difficulty or swelling. She was lethargic in appearance and slow to answer questions. She felt "foggy". She was oriented to person place and time. She had bilateral pedal pulses and was able to feel light touch in her feet an calves and able to lift feet up. Stroke assessment done.  No facial droop. She was able to smile equally. She was able to lift both arms equally. Her speech was not slurred but it was slow. Her baseline is unknown.  BP was taken again at 05:30 PM and was 160/90 with pulse of 120. She continued to feel dizzy and did not report any improvement in her symptoms. She was given the option for paramedics to be called which she was agreeable to. Paramedics arrived and patient reported no improvement in her symptoms. She was able to walk slowly from cot to stretcher and was transported to hospital.  She initially did not report any adverse reactions to her first COVID vaccine but upon further questioning she did say she felt palpitations and dizziness after her first vaccine but it went away so she did not report it to anyone.

Shoulders, chest, abdomen at which time I was slightly nauseas, and then slowly on to my knees when I became weak. The effects went on for several hours. These episodes went on for approx. 7 weeks. Not daily. In fact I didn't have another episode for several weeks. But at one time I had 11 days in a row. They lasted up to 4 hours. And several times I felt as though I would collapse when the effects reached my knees. But on the last week of the episodes, I could tell they were getting milder.
LAB_DATA: I tested glucose at the beginning, middle and end of several episodes - all normal. I also took blood pressure beginning, middle and end of several episodes - normal. I was sent for a CT scan - normal, and wore a heart monitor through a milder episode - normal.

Patient is a 41 yo woman with no PMH who presented to an  outside urgent care with left flank pain found to have a wedgelike defect in  the posterior left lower renal pole suggestive of a renal infarct.  She  underwent CTA which did not show any embolism, thrombus, dissection.  The  radiologist did note mild beading of the bilateral renal arteries, however the  radiologist at Valley View reviewed the images as well and was not as convinced.      Left renal infarct: Given suggestion of mild feeding of the bilateral  renal arteries, patient underwent CTA of the chest, head and neck which did not  show any other signs of fibromuscular dysplasia.  Echocardiogram did not have  any thrombus or decrease in function.  Patient did not have any arrhythmias on  telemetry.      Blood cultures were ordered and pending on discharge, but patient did not have  any of endocarditis      A hypercoagulable work-up including factor V Leiden, protein C, protein S,  Antithrombin, lupus anticoagulant, beta-2 microglobulin, anticardiolipin  antibodies were all sent and are pending at the time of discharge      Discussed the case with hematology at hospital: Most experts  treat with 3 months of anticoagulation other evidence is not entirely clear and  aspirin 81 mg may be a reasonable choice.  In light of the patient's lack of  insurance, decision was made to treat with 1 month of apixaban followed by 81  mg of aspirin daily indefinitely      Discharged with a short course of oxycodone 5 mg #15

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient returned to observation area two hours post injection complaining of LA pain. Medic on site observed some swelling to the LA and proceeded to provide an ice pack. After further assesment patient did not appear in any distress and was instructed to stay in observation for an additional 30 min. At approximately 1300 the patient began scratching  the vaccinated arm and mumbling in a language we could not understand. Immediately the interpreter was called and we prepared for an adverse reaction. Two of our LPNs began taking vitals, One RN began assessing the site where we noted possible infiltration to the subcutaneous tissues. We then moved the patient to a private room.                    RN chart note: "Patient crying sitting in chair, complains of L arm pain. Left arm swollen, softball size, hard to touch, patient sensation remains intact, left radial pulse +2 and present, patient can wiggle all fingers on command. Patient initially denied Benadryl, however after educated with safety and calling 911, patient denied ambulance, and agreed to IV placement. 20 g IV placed in Right AC, 50 mg IV push Benadryl once for swelling and itching of arm spreading in size, 500mL LR bag hung, Patient A0x4 on room air answering questions appropriately. Patient denied ambulance service at this time. Patient states headache is stronger and chest pain decreased."  Patient then fell asleep and approximately  at 1400 awoke with red eyes, continued headache that had gotten worse. BP retaken and was 162/102. At this point we decided we would need EMS to respond. With the language barrier and poor past medical history, we did not find it appropriate to continue treating the patient on site. She was still A&Ox4, denied restricted airways or significant chest pain. Our medical director was alerted of the event and instructed us to call EMS despite patient refusal. EMS arrived by 1430 and assessed patient, she finally agreed to transport.
CUR_ILL: Patient denied recent illness and prior SARS-CoV-19 illness.
HISTORY: Patient has a Hx of hypertension. Has not been consistent with taking medication. Prior to adverse reaction, she had not had her medication in several days.
ALLERGIES: Patient denied Hx of allergies to medication and food. No prior immunization reactions noted.

THE PATIENT INDICATED ON AGENCY FORM PREVACCINATION CHECKLIST FOR COVID-19 VACCINES QUESTION 2 THAT SHE HAD NOT PREVIOUSLY RECEIVED ANY DOSE OF COVID-19 VACCINE.  If a dose is inadvertently administered before the 4-day grace period, it does not need to be repeated. This means that when reviewing records, a second dose of Moderna COVID-19 Vaccine administered 23 or less days after the first dose does not need to be repeated. This is considered a vaccine administration error. Determine how the error occurred and implement strategies to prevent it from happening again. Additionally, you are required to report COVID-19 vaccine administration errors to the Vaccine Adverse Event Reporting System

I am still having them but they are milder now.  The next day after the injection.. I made an appointment with a cardiologist because they were still bad. She left the pharmacy.  About 10-15 minutes later we found out she was slumped over the steering wheel in her vehicle and EMS had been called. I followed up with her on 4/18/2021 and she said she was given benadryl and steroids to treat the reaction and was still recovering from the reaction.

Within hours of getting the shot, patients left eye started turning red. He visited a medical facility and they diagnosed him pink eye and gave him antibiotic drops. The drops did not seem to be working and by that Monday he went to see the eye doctor. Eye doctor said it was viral pink eye and thought it was strange that this came about right after the vaccine and in the eye on the same side he was vaccinated. Over the next days and weeks, the viral infection moved to the other eye. Both eyes stayed swollen, red and tearing constantly. He has lost some of his vision and says that things far away are very fuzzy looking. The doctor said it was the worst case of viral pink eye he has ever seen and that he would have it for the long haul of 4 to 6 weeks. He had to do a medical withdrawal from college due to missing too much of the nursing program he is enrolled in. The pinkeye is still ongoing and we don't know when it will be over.
LAB_DATA: He has had eye exams at the eye doctor and been there 3 times since this started. He also went to a medical facility before he visited the eye doctor. He went to his chiropractor hours after the first shot and the chiropractor noticed that his eye was turning red and told him about it then. I am unsure if any of the doctors did any laboratory testing. He did have eye exams at the eye doctor at each visit.

7.5 hours after receiving the Covid19 Vaccine, my nasal passages started burning. After about 30 min of my nasal passages burning (they continued to burn), I had a sudden onset of severe pain across my face in my sinus's. My upper teeth were also in pain. I could not drink anything hot or cold because it would cause a sharp shooting pain through my sinus's and would take several mins to subside. The pain continued the next day, so I went to immediate care but they refused to give me an antibiotic. They gave me a Covid test which was negative. 4 days after the extreme pain in my sinus's and teeth, I still had severe pain on the left side of my face, ear and teeth. I called my primary care physician and she prescribed a 10 day Augmentin antibiotic.  Finally my pain subsided 7 days after my vaccine (3 days after the start of antibiotics). 2 days after I finished the antibiotics, I had a sudden onset of severe pain in my hips and lower back, the pain persisted for a week. I went for acupuncture treatment and this eased my pain.  I just had my 2nd dose of the Covid19 vaccine and did not have any side effects.

On March 25, 8 days after the vaccine shot in my left arm, I began experiencing intense pain on the left side of my neck and head. By March 28 the pain had become so excruciating I went to an Urgent Care facility and they sent me to the Emergency Room. While in the ER I had blood tests and a CT scan which all came back negative. I was given Oxycodone-Acetaminophen for the pain and prescribed Cephalexin in case there was some type of infection. They also ruled out Shingles. I continued to have pain and contacted my Primary Care Physicians Office and spoke with one of the Physician Assistants two times the next week. She prescribed Baclofen 10 mg and took me off the Cephalexin and put me on Amoxycillin because we thought the problem might have been an ear infection. The next week I spoke with my Primary Care Physician, and he believed I was suffering from Trigeminal Neuralgia, so he put me on Carbamazepine 200 mg twice a day. That same week, on April 9, I was finally able to meet with the Physician Assistant at the Neurologists office and she also believed I was suffering from Trigeminal Neuralgia. I continued to take the Carbamazepine daily and the Baclofen and Oxycodone-Acetaminophen as needed. On Monday April 12 I informed the nurses at the Neurologist office that I was experiencing several symptoms/side effects that included dizziness, weakness, difficulty swallowing and a pounding heartbeat. The nurses talked with the PA and the PA took me off the Carbamazepine and put me on Oxcarbazepine 150 mg twice a day and she prescribed Methylprednisolone 4 mg. On Thursday April 15 I began to have intense prolonged pain behind my left ear down to the neck and in the Trigeminal nerves in the forehead and top of the head on the left side. I was in so much pain I slept for less than 2 hours. The next morning, I vomited and went to the Emergency Room again. At the ER they treated my pain with a headache IV cocktail that included Ibuprofen, Benadryl, an anti-nausea medication, Fentanyl, and a steroid. Within an hour my pain level dropped from a 9 to a 3 and I was released. The ER prescribed Gabapentin 300 mg (3 times a day) which I started the evening of April 16. I have had less constant pain since leaving the ER and starting the Gabapentin, but I continue to have pain in the Trigeminal nerve areas and neck with some flare ups that reach a 7 out of 10 in pain. I am scheduled for an MRI on April 23 and a visit with the Neurologist on May 10.
LAB_DATA: March 28: CT Scan and blood work at ER. No issues except elevated BP and pulse. April 9: Bloodwork- elevated liver (something) concerns. Elevated BP. April 16: 2nd ER visit: elevated pulse & BP.
OTHER_MEDS: Rosuvastatin 20 mg, Escitalopram 10 mg, Famotidine 20 mg, Sumatriptan SUCC 100 mg as needed, and Flonase Sensimist containing Fluticasone Furoate Nasal Spray 27.5 mcg per spray with Glucocorticoid (2 to 3 sprays per day).
HISTORY: GERD, migraines, degenerative disc between T10 and T11 Vertebrate, 2 bulging disks in lower back, neck pain radiating down to upper left arm

SYMPTOM_TEXT: I had my first dose of Covid 19 Pfizer vaccine on the 5th of April, 2021 at 1pm. I had sore arm and was fatigued which was expected. However, the day I had my vaccine was also the day my menstrual cycle started and just to assure myself I informed the pharmacist and asked if that was okay and they said it shouldn?t be a concern.   I was doing fine until toward the end of day 3. I was expecting my period to stop as it always does on 3rd day  but I started bleeding heavier that day there after. It didn?t worry me much until I started discharging huge blood clots  as big as an apple 2 times every after 30 mins from that moment.   I rushed to the ER later that night(still bleeding heavily with blood clots every now and then) but I was not admitted since my vitals and the blood counts were normal at that moment.   I went back home  and hoped the bleeding would stop but again with on pain or fever what so ever I kept bleeding all day. This is my 5th day of bleeding. Then on Sunday morning, I still kept bleeding heavy and I was too weak that I went back to the ER again.   This time , (day 6) I got admitted because I have had lost a lot of blood and I needed blood transfusion. My HB dropped from 11.3 to 6.7 and it went further down to 5 something. I got 3 units of blood transfusion in the ER. They did ultrasound, CT scans(with and without contrast) and still couldn?t figure out the cause of the bleeding. My uterus showed no problems but my body was not even responding to Tranexamic acid to stop the bleeding. So the doctor proceeded with an angiogram and did an emergency uterine artery Embolization to stop the blood supply to the uterus. The bleeding stopped there after and I started regaining my vitals.  However, the cause of the bleeding still remains unknown.
LAB_DATA: pregnancy - negative  ct scans and ultrasounds all said nothing.  They found a cyst but it wasn't the cause of the bleeding. uterine atery embolization

My ureter on the right caused the pain, and it spread to the right kidney in back. It is April 19, 2021 now. It eventually spread to my left ureter and left kidney. I had zero, ZERO illness and NO signs of a bladder infection prior. I've had 2 bladder infections in my 42 yrs and I went from fine to so sick I was scared. No trouble urinating, urine cloudy, pain etc. Just woke up literally 2 and a half days after my 1st shot and was sick. Am currently taking cefuroxime (Ceftin generic) 500mg every 12 hrs for 10 days I picked up Monday April 12. Also now took 12 mg Ivermectin (prescribed by a physician) Thursday April 15, 2021. A second dose Saturday April 17, 2021. Then I take it 2 weeks from the 17th, and 1 more time 2 weeks later.

After a few hours of getting the shot, felt tired and started feeling pressure in left chest - thought maybe it was my heart, but it gradually spread to my right chest, so I thought maybe then it was my lungs. The next day I felt worse, like I had COVID all over again, achy, low fever, miserable, but cough also came back. All only lasted about 24 hours (still have a slight pain in chest and tired today, 4 days later) but I had not heard that the first dose would cause that type of reaction, and definitely could not find anything anywhere about cough coming back. After googling, found an article in NY times about a doctor who experienced similar reactions -  https://www.google.com/amp/s/www.nytimes.com/2021/02/01/health/have-you-had-covid-19-coronavirus.amp.html.    I was sick for about three weeks after flying to and from in November 2020, and tested positive for antibodies in mid-December and tested positive for antibodies again the day before I received the vaccine, so based on that and the few articles I found online, it seems maybe if you get the vaccine after already having COVID, you react to the first dose and not the second. LAB_DATA: Called urgent care walk in clinic on April 11th and had a call back from a doctor to discuss my symptoms. He encouraged me to go to urgent care in person the following day.  I booked an appointment at urgent care on April 12th at 11:00am, and saw Dr, who diagnosed me with tennis elbow or Lateral epicondylitis of left elbow.   She asked me if I had problems opening jars or things with my left hand. I said no at the time, but when I got home, realized indeed, there was great pain when attempting to open a container. The pain is severe.  This is not my dominant arm, and this diagnosis is a repetitive use injury. I have not done anything repetitive with my left arm. No weight lifting. SYMPTOM_TEXT: Tingling and numbness in three left toes of left foot; tingling in pinkie/ring fingers of left hand; random "pings" (nerve-related) around body; mild tingling/numbness in lips. These symptoms concern me because I was hospitalized for Guillain-Barre Syndrome in July, 2020 and numbness/tingling in the feet was one of the initial symptoms of GBS. GBS is an auto-immune condition which can cause temporary paralysis and, depending upon its severity, death. It is is usually self-limiting but can take months or years to resolve. In early stages it can be treated with IV immunoglobulin to replace "bad" antibodies with "good" ones and that is the  five day treatment I had at  Hospital over the summer. I am very nervous that the Pfizer vaccine may be triggering another GBS episode though everything I have read says that there have been reported instances of this happening. Still, I thought it concerning enough to contact my primary care physician and website because GBS is no joke.
LAB_DATA: I have just reported these symptoms to my primary care physician and am awaiting her reply. I have also requested that she recommend a local GBS specialist because I am not sure whether or not to get a 2nd Pfizer dose in three weeks (as I am scheduled to do) even if these neurological symptoms resolve within a few days. My understanding is that patients have a bigger reaction to their second doses, so that raises huge alarm bells for me.
OTHER_MEDS: Synthroid 88 mg. daily Zoloft 25 mg. 3X per week; 50 mg. 4X per week Excedrin (1) Vitamin D (2000 ICU)
CUR_ILL: No, but I did have Guillain-Barre Syndrome in July, 2020 which resulted in my being hospitalized for five days and given IV/Immunoglobulin treatment for five consecutive nights. It took me almost two months to completely recover my strength, feeling in my feet and lower limbs, and ability to walk easily.
HISTORY: Thyroid cancer patient whose thyroid was removed 16 years ago and followed up with radioactive iodine 131 treatment. I am in remission as far as I know. Many follow-up scans were done for 5 years out from the surgery.
ALLERGIES: Slight allergic reaction to codeine (mild itching)

15 minutes after the injection I had an intense allergic/anaphylactic reaction.  I was watched and treated on site by EMS for 2 hours with Benadryl, oxygen and rest.  We did not use epi because I was still able to breath (minus some wheezing, coughing, hoarseness and lung irritation).  I felt the reaction hit when I started seeing green spots and my vitals dramatically increased (BP 181/111, HR 142 and weak).  I then experienced the following symptoms: rash/hives on neck and chest, fatigue and weakness, dizzy and lightheaded and needed wheelchair for moving around, chills and shaking, blurry vision, nausea, stomach pain, headache, chest pain and increased urination.  I also had elevated glucose (147).  During those two hours my vitals decreased a little, but the rest of my symptoms persisted.  I was not getting better and my vitals started to increase again at the two hour mark so EMS called an ambulance and transported me to hospital.  I was treated with solumedrol and observed for several hours.  The meds helped enough to send me home.  (I did have to continue taking Benadryl at home that night and the next day because I continued to have an allergic response). I also had severe injection site pain and bruising.

The next day when I woke-up around 10:00 a.m., I still had the aches and pains, all the way down to the bottoms of my feet. My body hurt to stand. The aches and pains continued that evening, along with diaherra and chest pains. The pains continued through Saturday and the chest pains got worse. The pain would radiate from my chest to my left arm, to my left shoulder, and into my back between my shoulder blades. Then by 7:00 p.m. or so on Saturday, my chest started to feel better and my aches and pains were not as bad. I was then woken up around 12:00 a.m. or so, on Saturday/Sunday with severe chest pains again with the radiation of pain. This also came along with the aches and pains and diahrrea. I tried to do simple putting my dishes away and loading up my dishwasher, and couldn't complete the task due to the chest pain and severe aches and pains all over my body. I received my first Moderna shot on April 1, 2021. On April 12th, I began experiencing what felt like air pressure issues in my right ear on and off throughout the day until April 14th, then I felt like I was loosing hearing on my right ear. On April 15th, exactly two weeks after recieving my first Moderna dose, I completely lost hearing on the right side of my ear and had awful ringing in my ear. I went to see a PCP and they could not diagnose me. On Monday, April 19th I went to see an ENT specialist, they did not find an infection or ear wax built up and said I may have Sudden Sensorineural Hearing Loss (SSHL) and prescribed me Prednisone. They were not 100% sure if the vaccine could be the cause but said it is a possibilty, especially as the number of people keeps increasing. My left hearing is perfect but my right is almost nonexistent.   I am 27 year old, female, petite and healthy. I have never had any hearing problems in my life and this occured within 2 weeks of my vaccination. It is difficult to hear and my quality of life just in the last week had diminished as it is overwhelming to drive, be in meetings, or even listen to music.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: The patient received the Janssen COVID-19 vaccine on 4/9/21 as documented in MIIC. This reporter has no other records of the day of administration.   Patient's last menstrual period was 07/22/2020 and Estimated Date of Delivery was Apr 28, 2021. On 4/11/21 at 0218, two days after administration of the COVID-19 vaccine, the patient was admitted to the University of Hospital Birthplace for spontaneous rupture of membranes x 7 hours contractions since 4/10/21 2330. Per discharge summary note 4/13/21 in EHR: ?The patient is a 33 year old now G4P2022 who presented to the Midwife service with rupture of membranes and subsequent onset of spontaneous labor. She was noted to have mild range blood pressure and transaminase levels double the upper limit of normal, meeting criteria for preeclampsia with severe features. This was noted just prior to complete cervical dilation and her delivery was completed by the service. She was subsequently transferred to the OB MD service for further management. Her postpartum course was uncomplicated. She was continued on magnesium for 24h postpartum. She was started on nifedipine XL 30mg for blood pressure management and her BPs were wnl. Her ALT downtrended from 137 to 109. Her AST downtrended from 139 to 70. Creatinine returned to baseline. On PPD#2, she was meeting all of her postpartum goals and deemed stable for discharge. She was voiding without difficulty, tolerating a regular diet without nausea and vomiting, her pain was well controlled on oral pain medicines and her lochia was appropriate. Her hemoglobin prior to delivery was 13.5 and after delivery was 11.2. Her Rh status was positive, and Rhogam was not indicated.? Per Labor and Delivery note 4/13/21:  ?Labor Course: arrived in active labor w SROM. Elevated BPs, abn PreE labs, new dx of PreE w severe features late in active labor, MD consult, plan to start Mag So4 after birth as patient was starting 2nd stage of labor as diag become clear. She progressed to complete and pushed, after which she had a spontaneous vaginal delivery.  No nuchal cord was noted. Apgars of 8 and 9   The cord was double clamped after 60 seconds and cut.  IV pitocin was started. The placenta was then delivered using gentle traction and suprapubic pressure. The uterus was noted to be firm after fundal massage.  The perineum was assessed for lacerations and none were noted. The placenta appeared intact with a 3V umbilical cord. See details in below: Pain meds: epidural IUP at 37 weeks gestation delivered on April 11, 2021.   SVD delivery of a viable Male infant. Weight : 6 pounds 4 ounces  Apgars of 8 at 1 minute and 9 at 5 minutes. Labor was spontaneous. Monday, April 12th, around 2pm I started to develop extreme stomach pain, as well as noticed some shortness of breath or elevated heart rate. The stomach pain worsened after dinner. I  assumed it was something I ate, which was the same thing I eat every day, and expected it was some type of gas that would resolve itself naturally. I went to bed in lots of pain. I didn't sleep well due to the issues and woke up still in pain in my mid stomach, mostly on the left side. I called the nurse who did an intake and advised that I go to the ER (Tuesday, April 13th)
LAB_DATA: At the ER (April 13th), I was given an EKG (Normal) and CT scan. The CT scan showed mild inflammation in the left upper quadrant of my colon and was diagnosed with mild diverticulitis and acute pancreatitis. I was given a prescription for antibiotics and put on a 3 day liquid diet and scheduled an immediate appointment with my GI doctor.  Upon visiting Dr. (GI doctor) on Thursday April 15th, I was informed that it was a case of Diverticulitis and based on its location (upper left quadrant) he wanted to do a colonoscopy and biopsy, due to the unconventional location of the diverticulitis. I was told to continue on my medication and start easing into foods, like rice and mash potatoes. He was surprised as am healthy and have no other symptoms that may have caused the disease.

SYMPTOM_TEXT: Patient received first COVID vaccine on 2/6/2021 and second vaccine on 3/6/2021. Patient presented to Hospital on 4/09/2021 for persistent nausea and vomiting, diarrhea, hematuria and jaundice. Patient reported a 1 month history of intermittent nausea and vomiting, generalized abdominal pain, feeling dizzy and weak, poor appetite. Patient had a colonoscopy ~2 weeks prior admission to hospital for cancer screening purposes which was unremarkable and labs done by his primary care at that time were all normal (per admitting physician's note). At hospital, patient was found to have evidence of hemolytic anemia thought to be autoimmune in nature with a positive direct antiglobulin. Patient was subsequently transferred to hospital on 4/11/2021 for further workup. Patient is still currently admitted to hospital. Oncology was consulted for workup of pancytopenia and suspected warm autoimmune hemolytic anemia. Throughout admission, the patient's platelets have ranged between 59-154 k/�L and hemoglobin has ranged 4.5-8.6 g/dL with no documented history of thrombocytopenia or anemia. Patient received methylprednisolone 125 mg x9 doses, prednisone 80 mg daily (1 mg/kg) x5 doses, prednisone 60 mg x1 dose, rituximab 740 mg (375 mg/m2)  x3 doses, and immune globulin 40 g x3 doses. Patient has also received 4 units of packed red blood cells. Given the timing of anemia and thrombocytopenia and unknown etiology, immune response to his COVID vaccine is on the differential.

I experienced they "typical" side effects of pain / aching at site of injection, chills, and muscle aches.  No problem.  What alarmed me was that  I also had greatly increased neuropathic pain.  I have chronic headaches due to cervical spine damage but these headaches were greatly magnified.  All my "usual" areas of pain due to existing injuries, mostly neuropathic, were greatly magnified.  Extreme low back pain started, so painful it hurt to lay on my back. The trip to get vaccinated wasn't long enough to trigger such extreme pain. I hardly slept due to the discomfort and extreme pain.  I experienced transient, strange pain, such as suddenly getting very sharp, stabbing pain in one toe on my right foot that lasted for about one (1) minute.  Same strange sudden sharp pain in my left knee while laying down, even though no known problems with that knee. I am physically fit. Very health conscious. A vegan.  This was easily one of the most total body painful experiences I have ever had.   It reminded me of one time I had a terrible bout of food poisoning, but with horrible nerve pain and without intestinal problems. I started taking Ibuprofen 800mg  the next morning and slept the rest of the day and night - since I got maybe 3 hours of interrupted sleep the night of the 2nd shot.  The day after that I was not 100% but much improved.  By the 3rd day post 2nd shot I felt normal.   Two other women in my social circle experienced similar reactions to the 2nd dose.   I read that more people with neuropathic and/or arthritic conditions are reporting similar reactions, and those with auto-immune conditions.  I would still get the vaccine - I would just have prepared better (doctor approved sleeping pills and pain medications.)
HISTORY: Hashimoto's thyroiditis - 21 years approximately.    2011 auto accident injuries - primary conditions still existing:  Cervical neuropathy and  cervical radiculopathy - approximately 7 years. SYMPTOM_TEXT: 1) Kidney infection - horrible pain; 2) Lost all hearing in left ear.  First shot - February 11, 2021.  Second shot - March 12, 2021. Further testing on April 12 showed elevated WBC, Above normal Squamous cell counts and Transitional cell counts and elevated Leukocyte Esterase.   Next test in a week.  However, feeling OK.  NOTE:  3 OTHER PEOPLE I KNOW GOT KIDNEY INFECTION WITH VACCINE!  2) APRIL 11:  Sudden Sensorineural hearing loss, or SNHL.  Audiology exam on April 12 confirms total hearing loss in left ear.  Predinsone and steriod shot in ear drum.  No change as of April 19 - completely deaf in left ear with ongoing whoosing in the background.

CUR_ILL: None - completely healthy.  No kidney infections for over a decades

Within 24 hours of receiving the vaccine, hives developed on my left thigh. The tongue swelling, shortness of breath and faintness happened on and off for the first day. It resolved on its own by the next day. The hives got progressively worse and peaked roughly 48 hours after getting the vaccine. They slowly faded, but are still faintly noticeable. I had general malaise  for the rest of the week. I have photos showing the progression of the hives.
LAB_DATA: I notified the hospital where I received the vaccine of my reaction on Tuesday April 6th but they informed me that they only monitor for symptoms during the 15 minute waiting period and my only option was to see a PCP or the ER. I do not have a PCP and cannot afford an ER visit, so I decided to just monitor my symptoms as they were not emergent and ultimately did not have to go.

I continued to have sweats, chills, and after about another hour body aches set in.  My whole body was cramping up and my hands were shaky.  I was very short of breath over short movements like to get to the bathroom, I would be out of breath and dizzy.   Around 1700  (6 hours post shot) I took Tylenol and continued to take it every six hours.  I was able to keep ginger ale and crackers down but didn't eat much else until the next morning.  I think the fever broke in the night.  The next morning I was just really tired and sore, but much less achy than the day prior.   I was able to eat light meals  and I stopped taking Tylenol sometime that mid-morning.  I felt fine the next day (about 48 hours after the shot).

March 15th: Day 2 after vaccine: noticeable shortness of breath when walking  March 17-18:  Days 4 and 5 after vaccine: extreme fatigue/exhaustion March 20-24: Burning chest pain, pain in jaw, continued shortness of breath when walking and fatigue March 24: Went to doctor, D-Dimer = .51 March 25: Chest X-ray to rule out pulmonary embolism. No pulmonary embolism found. Enlarged lymph nodes on left side found. April 4: After 1/2 mile walk was exhausted. Experienced loss of strength in both hands, but more so in right hand. Experienced "general feeling of doom/unwellness" previously associated with seizure due to oligodendroglioma. April 3: Follow up with doctor. Suggested my brain tumor (oligodendroglioma) may be growing. April 6th: MRI. Tumor had not grown. April 7th: Meeting with oncologist who did not feel symptoms were due to tumor growth. Suggested possibility that vaccine could have triggered breakthrough seizure. Increased seizure medication in mornings from 50 mg Vimpat to 100 mg Vimpat.  Sent me to my regular doctor. Met with regular doctor, who didn't think symptoms were due to the vaccine, but didn't know because it was so new. Did bloodwork. Severe fatigue in afternoon. April 10th: Was scheduled for 2nd vaccine, but did not feel well enough to get it. April 12th: All bloodwork normal except high LDL (but good ratio with HDL), high TPO (thyroid antibodies). Still fatigued. April 11-17: Fatigue gradually improving. Shortness of breath going away. Stamina returning, gradually. April 18-19: Feeling much better. Able to walk. No shortness of breath.

Received 2nd covid vaccination last week- mild reaction with fever thereafter.  She had w/u in the ED including an EKG with inferior and septal TWI and trop of 1.61.  CTA chest was negative.
